Apartments for sale in St. Petersburg - real estate market analysis.

Yandex.Real.Estate is an archive of ads for the sale of apartments in St. Petersburg and neighboring settlements for several years. We need to learn how to determine the market value of real estate. Our task is to set the parameters. This will allow the client to build an automated system: it will track anomalies and fraudulent activity.

Two types of data are available for each apartment for sale. The first ones are entered by the user, the second ones are obtained automatically based on cartographic data. For example, the distance to the center, airport, nearest park or pound (river).

Description of the data (columns).¶

  • airports_nearest — distance to the nearest airport in meters (m)
  • balcony — number of balconies
  • ceiling_height — ceiling height (m)
  • cityCenters_nearest — distance to the city center (m)
  • days_exposition — how many days the ad was placed (since publication to removal)
  • first_day_exposition — date of publication
  • floor — floor
  • floors_total — total floors in the house
  • is_apartment — apartments (boolean type)
  • kitchen_area — kitchen area in square meters (m²)
  • last_price — price at the moment of publication
  • living_area — living area in square meters (m²)
  • locality_name — name of the locality
  • open_plan — free layout (boolean type)
  • parks_around3000 — number of parks within a 3 km radius
  • parks_nearest — distance to the nearest park (m)
  • ponds_around3000 — number of pounds within a radius of 3 km
  • ponds_nearest — distance to the nearest pound (m)
  • rooms — number of rooms
  • studio — studio apartment (boolean type)
  • total_area — the total area of the apartment in square meters (m²)
  • total_images — the number of photos of the apartment in the ad

Work plan.¶

  • Upload data, check duplicates, omissions, etc., correct types and obvious errors (typos), filter out unrealistic and incorrigible data.
  • Add columns with new calculated data.
  • We will display histograms by columns, study the number of floors and distances to the nearest parks, airports, etc.
  • We will look at the publications by day of the week. We'll study the prices of objects, including for 1 m², check the correlations and relationships between the parameters.
  • Consider the behavior of average prices and prices in cities with the largest number of ads, as well as in cities that are price leaders.
  • We'll check how the average price of 1 m² behaves when moving away from the city center.

In [7]:
def lost_data(df):
    out = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['column_names','gaps','lost_portion'])
    i = 0
    for column in df.columns:
        if df[column].isna().sum() > 0:
            out.loc[i] = [column, df[column].isna().sum(), round(df[column].isna().sum()/len(df), 4)]
            i += 1
    print(f"Columns missing data, with gaps {i} of {len(df.columns)}")
    out.set_index('column_names', inplace=True)
    return out


print(lost_data(data).sort_values('lost_portion'))

Comment.

  • ceiling_height - it is impossible to fill in 39% of the gaps, we will not.
  • floors_total there are only 86 omissions, almost zero, if necessary, we will delete the empty ones.
  • is_apartment - 88% do not fill it. It would be logical to fill in the gaps as "no" in the next section.
  • kitchen_area - it can be assumed that these are passes for housing, where the kitchen space is not allocated (not separated), 10% looks plausible.
  • We do not supplement the geo-positions calculated by Yandex, omissions from 23% to 66% - it is unclear whether this is normal or bad, it would be good to ask the developers of this software.
  • Omissions in days_exposition will not be counted, because there are no dates for removing ads.
  • Possible reasons for the unfilled cells: ceiling_height is considered not particularly important or a losing side, is_apartment is filled in as needed, balcony is similarly not specified, so there is no balcony (which is unrealistic).

In [25]:
def press(c_name):
    return c_name.replace('ё','е').replace('городского типа','')

# Let's form 2 lists, original and compressed

names = data['locality_name'].unique()
names_compressed = []
for cty in names:
    new = press(cty)
    if new not in names_compressed:
        names_compressed.append(new)
        
len(names), len(names_compressed)  # let's see if there is a difference in the lists - 34
Out[25]:
(364, 330)

# Changing the names of localities. We can apply the press function throughout the column, but 
# for the sake of training, we will apply it only to those lines where the names are not compressed

ind = data.query('locality_name not in @names_compressed').index
data.loc[ind,'locality_name'] = data.loc[ind,'locality_name'].apply(press)

data.query('locality_name not in @names_compressed')['locality_name'].count() # no duplicates

  • There are a lot of columns with whole data and omissions. If we bring it to the int type, then you need to remove the omissions, because Pandas stores such columns in the float type (read on stackoverflow.com , and I noticed myself that NaN belongs to the float type).
  • We will see later if we will need integers, and we will return to this question if necessary.
  • floors_total , balcony columns were converted from float64 to int type: this way it will take less memory and it is more convenient to work later (including on graphs).

General conclusions.¶

  • The study analyzed a dataset of ads for real estate sales in St. Petersburg and the region, submitted in the period from November 2014 to May 2019. The number of analyzed rows is ~ 18000. The range of the cost of objects is from 12 thousand rubles to 763 million rubles, the spread of the total area is from 12 to 900 sq.m, in buildings with a height of 1 to 60 floors, with a number of balconies up to 5, the distance to the nearest ponds and reservoirs is from 13 to 1300 meters. There are objects that were sold in 1 day, but there are also objects that have been on sale for more than 4 years.
  • Data preparation, removal of explicit and implicit duplicates, as well as omissions in the data were carried out in the work. Calculation tables are presented, 26 graphs and histograms are studied, to which descriptions and explanations are given. Graphs and calculations are averaged and can serve as a criterion for the anomaly of the submitted ads (i.e., the basis for checking for falsification) if the numbers in the ads differ too much from the average.
  • Half as many ads are served on weekends as during the week. Average (not median) prices jump from Friday to Saturday, which means that ads with an increased price are served on Friday.
  • It is interesting that with the increase in the number of floors, the average area of the objects sold also grows. That is, with the rise to the top, sales become "more wholesale".
  • The decrease in the average price of 1 sq.m. in St. Petersburg at a distance from the center is non-monotonous: in the range of 3-7 km, prices even rise, not fall (the rise in price of 1 sq.m is +8660 rubles/km). The reduction in the cost of 1 sq.m in the range of 8-29km is on average 1320 rubles/km.
  • Basically, housing is for sale at a distance of 2-17km from the center. At a distance of about 30 km from the center, the price drops by almost 3.4 times.
  • Average price per square meter in St. Petersburg (2nd place, 114680r/sq.m.) is not as high as in Zelenogorsk (1st place) - 115123 rubles per meter. With a price of 84758 rubles per meter Peterhof (10th place) closes the rating of the most expensive settlements of the Leningrad region.
  • The real estate market in the Leningrad region sank after 2014, at the end of the period under review there is a tendency to its recovery.
